metadata.name: Dance of the Bald Eagles
metadata.description:
Every November, Bald Eagles migrate to Haines, Alaska, to prey for salmon on the Chilkat River. 

This is when the Chilkat River is half-frozen and the salmon are swimming very slowly up the river.  

The Bald Eagles are waiting on the trees for their opportunity to “bag” fresh fish.  
While diving from the trees to the river, they sometimes crash into each other and by shielding their talons they avoid harming each other.  Their talons are sharp as a razor blade.

In this photograph, the Bald Eagles are diving for the salmon and just before they crash into each other their eyes “lock” and their talons meet.  

This is a uniquely powerful shot of a nanosecond movement in nature.
